🚀 1. Why StampedLock Exists

    ReentrantReadWriteLock is good, but:

    ❌ Has overhead (tracking threads, reentrancy)
    ❌ Read lock still blocks under contention
    ❌ No optimistic reads

🔥 Enter StampedLock

    👉 Features:

    Optimistic read (non-blocking)
    Read lock
    Write lock
    No reentrancy (important!)

🧠 3. Optimistic Read (GAME CHANGER)
Flow:
Read without locking → Check if safe → Retry if needed
💡 Why powerful?

👉 No blocking
👉 Very fast for read-heavy systems

⚠️ Important
long stamp = lock.tryOptimisticRead();

👉 This does NOT lock anything

🔥 4. Internal Concept (Stamp)

Each lock operation returns a:

stamp = version of lock state

Used to:

Validate
Unlock
⚠️ 5. Critical Corner Cases
❗ 1. No Reentrancy
lock.writeLock();
lock.writeLock(); // ❌ DEADLOCK
❗ 2. Must use stamp correctly
lock.unlockWrite(stamp);

👉 Wrong stamp → IllegalMonitorStateException

❗ 3. Optimistic read is unsafe
int x = value; // may be stale

👉 Always validate!

❗ 4. No Condition support

Unlike ReentrantLock ❌

⚔️ 6. StampedLock vs ReadWriteLock
    Feature	        StampedLock	    ReadWriteLock
    Optimistic read 	✅	            ❌
    Reentrant	        ❌	            ✅
    Performance	🔥       🔥	            🔥
    Complexity	        High	        Medium

🔬 8. AQS (AbstractQueuedSynchronizer) Deep Dive

👉 Backbone of most locks in Java

📦 Used by:
ReentrantLock
Semaphore
CountDownLatch
ReentrantReadWriteLock
⚠️ Important

👉 StampedLock does NOT use AQS
👉 It uses custom synchronization (for performance)

⚙️ 9. How AQS Works
Core idea:
state + queue + CAS
🔹 State
volatile int state;

Represents:

Lock count
Permits
etc.
🔹 Queue
Thread queue (FIFO)
🔹 Flow
Try acquire → fail → join queue → park → wake up → retry
🔥 10. AQS Example (Simplified)
while (!tryAcquire()) {
    enqueue();
    park();
}
⚠️ 11. Real Production Problems
❌ 1. Lock contention

Too many threads → performance drop

❌ 2. Deadlocks

Especially with:

multiple locks
lock upgrading
❌ 3. Priority inversion

Low priority thread holding lock

🔥 12. When to Use What
Scenario	Use
Simple sync	synchronized
Moderate concurrency	ReentrantLock
Read-heavy	ReadWriteLock
Ultra high-performance reads	StampedLock
🧠 13. Expert-Level Insight

👉 StampedLock is best when:

Reads >> Writes (like 1000:1)
🚀 14. Interview Killer Answer

StampedLock improves performance using optimistic reads and avoids blocking.
It sacrifices reentrancy and simplicity for higher throughput in read-heavy scenarios.